Many Sydney libraries do 3d printing for a small fee too, but only small amounts.  Heaps of Libraries of Things across Australia, Canberra's has a huge volume and diversity of stock.  Red Earth City used community funds to buy the shed at 1111 Deepwater Road Matong. It has electricity, but not much else.  There are already several trillion legal structures running burns. If you want to start one, rather than starting from scratch, simply ask if you can operate under their existing compliance umbrella.

qid300_10_text: Honesty and directness, follow through and accountability, pretty anti-gaslighting or scapegoating
qid236_text: It's as much of a subconscious experience of growth, play and exploration as anything - like a beautiful generative sleep walk Filling our cups up, filling one anothers cups up Living as an example of how you want to be in life, how you want to show up in community Sometimes it can be a really cliquey mob but it can also be deeply connected in a way that's very real As well as a place of deep play, there's loads of work to do, there are always many jobs There's a raw elemental nature to it that can really test you - cold, heat, fire, water, dust  There's a real spiritual side to it to, through the burn sacraments, through the thresholds we pass through to enter and to exit, through shared principles we all commit to. It's not just a conventional space, it's a metaphysical one to a good extent. A temporary mutual ritual, or series of collected rituals which connect at the edges.  It can foster great kindness and also sometimes great cruelty  It can play out many of the normal toxic and beautiful dynamics of humanity writ large as a spectacle, as a playground to try things on in short form We can dissociate a lot out there, and there's the ketamine dust to prove it We can also closely face our shared humanity together too  So much joy, play, reverence, and in many ways a more grounded reality than the one we deal with most of the time  Something we can take home with us, and also something we can lose sight of in the everyday of conventional colonialist capitalist life.   There's a lot to it, and what that is is a factor of what we make of it together.   It's not a hierarchically designed festival event domineeringly led by 4 people in a mad rush that's for sure....   Or dominated by 2 misguided hippies playing very unpopular god for 14 years.    Whoever tries to dominate it fails, including me. It's a collectively emergent mystery.

qid248_text: Possibly one large bi-annual burn 5000+ in size with longer travel time alongside slightly smaller spread of annual regional burns with shorter travel time 1500+ in size.  In NSW I think that the two sweet spots are 1. Sydney / Melbourne equidistant zone, such as the Matong site. 2. Sydney / Northern Rivers equidistant zone, such as New England or Mid North Coast regions. Perhaps it would be be good to have an annual burn in each of those two zones in different seasons, such as one around April/May and one in September/October.
qid276_text: Democracy and engagement.

qid283_text: NSW is a large state, the travel times are extensive across its entirety.  I think the future might best become two burns annually each of a substantial size, One in the current zone such as Matong servicing south coast, ACT and VIC visitors, the other in the Mid North Coast or New England region servicing Northern Rivers, Newcastle and visitors from South Eastern Queensland.   It is also conceivable that there would rather be one larger bi-annual burn situated in the southern zone, complemented by another slightly smaller annual in the northern zone.  Immediately into 2026 I do not think that Third Degree or Underland should be considerations regarding appropriate dates, these are both small events with Third Degree being particularly restrictive for its site, this is not inclusive.
qid284_text: Listen to the theme camp leads they have wisdom and represent community.  It is probably best to plan for a 2026 burn on October long weekend with the acceptance that we may not burn. Alternatively a late September date may be considered without a long weekend. Getting away from the Big Burn date is helpful and advised. We should not be deferring to smaller events that are not properly inclusive, the community is suffering and shrinking.  Regarding financial structure, grants, ticket tiering, date and crew structure; 2019 was a great year, for now perhaps we should be following what worked well in the past.

qid241_text: A strong mission, vision and values statement for the org I’m volunteering with. Efficient and effective collaboration that protects team members from burnout. A culture in the org that enable issues to be discussed as they arise using a format that is widely known, understood and effective.

qid248_text: I like having many smaller burns each year that are closer to the communities the participants reside in. Although my favourite size for a burn is about 2k people max. and I’d like to see this size burn again on the east coast, but every 2-3years would be plenty.

qid307_text: Some more transparency around the financial status of Seed and the release of some after burn reports that clearly show what mistakes were made so the community can be aware and we can all work at avoiding the same mistakes going forward. Nobody in their right mind would support any version of seed right now without the release of those documents and some honest, open and vulnerable conversations between sunburnt arts, sunburnt events and the broader community.   The local community and resources around Matong have all deteriorated over the past few years. Things like loosing Brian Jones, a REC director moving in permanently, the CFA contacts changing, forestry contacts changing - all of this means the report that was built up in the community has diminished - and that needs fixing. If Seed is to be held in Matong (which it probs shouldn’t btw - for a variety or reasons) the local community connections need to start from ground up again. Org need to get out there and do some community engagement.

qid300_10_text: Quiet time - eg sound off after say 3am to allow for sleep. And quiet times to allow for conversation and social connection.
qid236_text: I’m there for the art and the community. I love a party and a dance like everyone else but for me, the ideology of the art movement that is burning man has always been the motivation and inspiration for me. Building huge things, crazy things, things that move, things that are dangerous and integrate fire, in collaboration with others - where else do you get to do this? I love the radical creative expression and the principles. And I love the freedom. I like to provide a framework that gives people permission to bring their creativity and experiment with it.
qid238_13_text: Willingness to ‘step up’ comes down to capacity and stress levels - what’s going on in my life!
qid241_text: Clear schedule and brief BEFORE the event, good organization so I know where I need to be when and for how long. Plus what I need to do.
qid243_text: The thing that puts me off is politics. And ego jostling. I’ve worked professionally for 30 years in design and have done leadership and governance training. I’m not interested in working with people who make decisions based on emotion rather than rationality. And I don’t want to have to manage difficult personalities in a volunteer role. It makes for too much stress in something that should be fun. Reduce the admin! It doesn’t need to be quite so admin heavy IMHO. And it’s a BIG ask - maybe also consider offering free tickets to the coordination team. They put in 100’s of hours over a year. It’s a simple, cheap thing and the least that could be done to show appreciation and make people feel valued.
qid244_text: With running my own theme camp, not too many. My theme camp runs very smoothly on the whole. Main issue is with crew ‘reverse gifting’ because they think they’re being helpful and contributing! I appreciate the grants - very helpful.  Had a minor concern about placement at Seed 2023 - site design could’ve been better thought through. (Ie not putting a family friendly camp next to an x-rated one!)  With other theme camps, I’ve had issues with poor management and leadership, lack of organization and people throwing tantrums and walking out, meaning I somehow end up being dumped with having to do everything. For example, three times I’ve had to be the one to pack down The Orphanage and get everything loaded onto trailers to get them offsite by gate closing times, including hauling rubbish and stuff left behind - both at Seed and Third Degree. Even though I’m not even a camp member! (Our theme camp often camps with them though.) Not going back for a fourth time though…  Gotta say though that it’s a HUGE effort to get everything out to Seed and costs a bomb in fuel etc. I’d much prefer to focus on more local events now that there are some. Not sure I’d make the trip out to Matong again - would have to be a very special event indeed to draw me back out there.
qid245_text: Yes! We collaborate with other camps all the time. I love sharing skills and creative ideas. We’ll be looking to collab and create more shenanigans again at Third this year.   We’ve collabed with: - Harmony Lab on music jams - Erstwhile Manor on cabarets - hosted Camp Allegedly’s Big Dress Parade  - held music jams, workshops and art events with The Orphanage / Rainbow Lounge  Planning future collabs with - Red Earth Brewery - Sarah B - Debonair Mantsion
qid247_text: Catbus broke a wheel at Seed 2023 due to people misusing him. So I guess safety and people treating ‘toys’ with respect.   All other art I’ve done has gone well - no issues.
qid248_text: I like as many as I can get to! Love the smaller, regular burns and burning pubs. I also attend fundraisers and other ‘burner/burn adjacent’ events. Any opportunity to hang out with my burner friends and I’m there!   I’d be happy to go to a ‘big burn’ if the location was good.   My favourite big burn so far is Kiwiburn - would def go back to that one. Loved the engagement, shenanigans and pranks there.   I’d like to experience lots of different regional burns and want to go to Blazing Swan, Afrikaburn and some of the SE Asia burns.
qid276_text: The variety and range of events and activities. I think the best thing that’s happened is the implosion of Seed - it’s allowed for new things to sprout, which was always the intention.
qid307_text: Less politics, less ego, more fun and kindness. Actively supporting people to get involved and have a go, even if their initial efforts are ‘mediocre’ - giving people permission and support is what inspires them to aim higher!
qid279_text: No idea, sorry. Aside from already known sites, such as Castle Mountain or Glenworth Valley. Most of the venues I’ve known seem to have been shut down sadly.
qid281_text: Not specifically, aside from Sparkhaus and Reverse Garbage. But I do think it would be worth considering having a communal storage unit for storing large, repeatable artworks/mutant vehicles and equipment.  I also liked the way the Kiwiburn art team had a shared library of tools for artists to ‘borrow’ onsite. And they offered a maker space onsite for artists and theme camps to create signage or repair costumes, decor etc.   I’d also be in favour personally of encouraging reuse, upcycling and using materials found in things like council cleanups for temporary art, especially things to be burned, rather than spending a fortune at Bunnings. And I’d also like to encourage reuse of art - current grants really only support creation of new art. But what about encouraging artists to bring back existing work or building on it? And helping to fund transport costs? Sustainability is just as important as leave no trace IMHO.    Shared transport options to get large scale art / mutant vehicles to site would also be a good thing to consider as well. Reduced carbon footprint.
qid282_text: For what purpose? I think that might help to indicate suitable orgs etc. Not sure what the connection goals would be…
qid283_text: Go back to grassroots and keep it radical, experimental and creative. Be flexible, open to new ideas/ways and be progressive - don’t be stuck with ‘this is how it’s done in America / how it’s always been done’ as this leads to meaningless cults and stagnation. Don’t let it become all about DJ’s, drugs and doof. At the heart, burns are an arts and counter culture movement. Let’s be that!! Because I think now, more than ever, our society needs this.

qid236_text: Connection to people. IE Community. A feeling that I matter. The chance to let others be seen so that they feel they matter.
qid241_text: Early organisation by team leads BEFORE the event. Meeting people BEFORE the event. Knowing what we are doing and how. Nothing it worse then being a volunteer who has no idea what is going on or how they are helping or who to ask. That is a demoralising feeling that leaves you wondering why you are wasting your time.
qid243_text: Being empowered to make decisions to flatten what often becomes a tall top down pyramid. Clear expectations of what needs to be delivered and then the freedom to execute that. Think a requirements doc for whatever team / role you are leading.
qid244_text: In running theme camps getting quality dependable people can be difficult. Without that it is difficult to delegate and let go. In general the ability to let go with a theme camp is a skill that takes practice. It has two aspects. First is the ability to attract the talent you need. The second is the ability to let go of control. Their is also an ever growing issue with the doco beig asked for. The benefits of being a formal theme camp are honestly not huge. The burden is significant. Soooo many forms. Soo many sticks and not enough carrot. I suspect more and more people will go rogue.
qid245_text: Power collaboration. Mixed results amongst the camps. Power was delivered. Not all in the collaboration were able to effectively use it. This was mostly an individual camp failure but would have been caught pre-paddock with more testing in addvance. Issue was technical one that effected a partner camp - rather then my own.
qid248_text: One (or two) BIG burns. Note big is people number. Nothing to do with camps, art, burn structures or central admin.  As many smaller events (< 400) as people want to organise. I think for these it is important that their tone and target audience be converyed clearly. Mostly as not all (sadly are young and old people welcoming).
qid276_text: Not a lot. Some camps have solid connections to others where there are tight friendships outside of burn events.  Very much everything seems individuals above their own camps above their own burns above prospective big burns above burner culture generally.
qid307_text: Possibly I am just more exposed to it now but far too many people think they are important for the roles they are inhabiting. Ego is rampant. Have encountered situations where people are treated differently as they are 'important'. It may be the way the world works but it disgusts me just the same. "Don't you know who I am" feels stronger to me now then the day I joined the burner world. Like I say that was probably just ignorance is bliss.

qid236_text: It’s like coming home…. I’ve been attending burn events since 2014, I know what to expect and how I can contribute, it’s an equal balance of familiarity and brand new people, art & experiences.  Also a fan of the bonding experience that comes through planning, prepping, building before the event
qid241_text: Clear, obvious comms about what trainings are happening, when & where. I often find out too late or retrospectively  For example; after 11 years in the community, I can count on 1 hand the number of ranger training sessions I’ve seen
qid248_text: Seed, around 2000-2500 people was perfect. Enough physical space & theme camp options to keep us busy & entertained, but also plenty of space to kick back / recharge / do my own thing
qid276_text: Seems like there are some grass roots / new blood theme camps / small events popping up. Super important to keep it fresh & bring new energy
qid307_text: I’m not sure, I’m in VIC so only see things from a distance
qid309_text: Hahaha. Is this a trick question??! With the safety 3rd approach I’ve seen / participated in amongst our community, it’s impossible to say :)
qid283_text: I’d love to see the community thriving - regular fundraisers / theme camp events, new people / camps / ideas popping up
qid284_text: My answers to your financial questions here might seem stingy and I realise operating costs are ever increasing, however my own living coats have increased too, so it has to represent value for money. Given that there are additional expenses eg contributing to mine & other camps’ fundraisers, camp dues so we can provide alcohol / food for gifting, plus my own gifts & supplies, it adds up to be an expensive weekend, with minimum infrastructure / facilities / headline DJs provided as part of the ticket cost  Hoping y’all can find a middle ground between profitability & viability  Also, I think there is some residual burnout / frustration amongst the community about what happened with the previous leadership / Board of Directors. I’ve seen the comms on socials about drawing a line in the sand / moving forward under new leadership / letting it go, but I think maybe the level of burnout / disengagement caused has perhaps been underestimated. Other than the comments section, which tends to get toxic / passive aggressive (and subsequently shut down / dismissed) very quickly, I think that maybe more is needed to facilitate the community moving forward.  I think after COVID stopped play, then the leadership fiasco played out, then many camps conscientiously objected to the last Seed, then 2025 tix were so expensive (I didn’t buy one)… there have been many concurrent reasons for Burners to feel disengaged / disheartened and to turn their attention elsewhere.  That said. I’m not sure what the answer is; theme camp liaison? Actively creating a forum & holding space for people’s experience of the previous iteration?  We have a passionate, creative, articulate & enthusiastic community, whether or not the damage can be repaired and the event can be financially viable, remains to be seen.  I’ll be watching for ways to get involved.  Burn bright

qid241_text: Role clarity and recognition are important as is workload balance. My experience volunteering was not with burning seed - however we put considerable work in on specific activities we were asked to do only to have this all basically disregarded and overruled which felt very disempowering.  I have also felt fully at capacity with my contributions in the theme camp space that volunteering on site isn’t something I’ve actively sought out as a way to contribute further.
qid243_text: I think it’s important to provide a framework structure and the ability for people to be able to connect and communicate / self organise.  Sometimes we need to go back to smaller, simpler operating models and allow evolution and growth to happen naturally.  Working with volunteers can be challenging if there are specific expectations regarding task execution.   I’m on the view that a clearly agreed outcome can be more empowering than a clearly defined task list if that makes sense.
qid244_text: Theme camp coordination is hard. Theme camps are hard!!!  There is so much work that happens behind the scenes that is un seen and carried out by often a select few.  Investment requires time, money, blood, sweat and tears!!!  Personally, in the recent (post covid) years, the juice hasn’t been as fresh and nice - yet the squeeze has felt a lot harder.  Theme camp politics are a thing but politics is kind of everywhere….  Not having regular burns makes recruitment hard - these things take time to grow and evolve and they do burn people out also.  Organisers at times seem burnt out and exhausted - and communication styles can at times feel abrasive.
qid245_text: Yes. 20 of us were hosted by Kamp Koasis at blazing swan when we took the ksub over. At burning seed (2018/2019) we had an informal village where we shared power and tried to communicate and collaborate on event run times to support and not clash with unique performances / experiences of our neighbour camps  This mostly went well except for a one event where we had a 20kva generator that required replacement and we realised that impacted 4 sound camps on a Friday night - luckily it was sorted in an hour or two!
qid276_text: As a Victorian I’m starting to feel excluded by the consistent references to nsw community and don’t feel I can answer this question.
qid307_text: As above, I am of the view that the Victorian burner community (and so perhaps nsw too) could look to blazing swan in some ways.  There’s a level of ego and pretentiousness in Victoria that isn’t as present at blaze/in WA.  I’m not sure what drives that…. But I think there’s a level of jadedness but maybe also some broader culture aspects.

qid276_text: People want to be part of the community and enjoy coming together,
qid307_text: Leadership. I think lots of people got burned out this year with seed not happening and then the big push for embers. We need people who have a vision and happy to lead. Seems to be plenty of opinions that are important, however, need to be balanced with doers and a defined goal. I personally believed we must rise from the embers and grow organically as numbers grow rather than strive to draw huge crowds to an event off the bat after so many false starts. Lets do the small thanks great and grow with confidence.

qid281_text: I have a wide range of tools for building that I can bring and make available for DPI
qid282_text: Confest Sydney and Confest at large. They have a proven vol structure that has been built over many, many years, and it would be great to seek advice on how to grow and get around issues as they have managed. (owning their land is a big part of that) Neo crew
qid283_text: Slow incremental growth focuses on building the right community, the right support, and practicing nailing all the things before trying to grow too big. If we do that and great a solid following of dedicated burners who all contribute in some way and Melbourne does the same with Underland, then we as two groups could have another crack of putting on an event as two coequal branches, in Matong or a contest site or elsewhere, bringing communities and knowhow together into something glorious. My vision is a Confest organisation but with pumping tunes and more party nutrients. People who build up themed camps and are rewarded for their efforts and are driven to do more and more with support rather than the weight being crushing to a few. Confest has a mandated 2 hours vol, there are many opportunities, and people really lean into it and helps with a feeling of ownership and responsibility.  It should really be a collection of people who would love to put on their own festival, providing sound camps and themed camps that become a tapestry of awesomeness, then we burn something :)
qid284_text: I love this survey, great job, good questions.  I think we need a hard reset, review of the whole structure, how decisions are made. Personally, when there is politics and things stagnate (loss of sight of the goal) I opt out. If from this we can develop a solid mission statement, we can get behind that guides our decision making (rather than the loudest or more persistent voice) the we will be on the right track.

qid236_text: I am drawn to Burner events by the ability to create spaces, experiences and connections that are, at the start, outside and beyond what is easily achievable in day-to-day life but, eventually, have the capacity to transform the way we live daily. After decades of Burning globally, I am convinced that our community has and is continuing to make an impact far outside and beyond the events themselves. This is very important to me. Also, I am a hedonist and love to enjoy and share pleasures with like-minded people, and I find burns to be an excellent venue for this.
qid241_text: I think it's good as is. No need to make it a bigger deal. When it comes to workload balance, I am very conscious of my own time and effort limitations, and offer my time and effort accordingly.
qid243_text: I like the self-organised, mildly anarchic nature of it. No need to structure it any more.
qid244_text: My own time availability. I believe I have contributed positively every time, but there's no question that I rank in bottom 50% of contributors. Until I retire from my work, that's not going to change
qid245_text: Yes, it was some minor sharing of resources and offerings. It went well, but it was easy.
qid248_text: One big annual burn in a season where the climate is pleasant, plus several smaller burns. I am not a huge fan of burner pubs, but warehouse parties are great.
qid276_text: I have been in so long that I know most people very well, and engage with them outside and beyond burner events.
qid307_text: This is not specific to the burner community, but I wish there was something other than platforms based on social media (e.g. Facebook) to communicate the existence of events, burn-related or not. Our community is so knowledgeable of what cool things are going on in NSW, in terms of arts, festivals, gatherings. I wish we had a one-stop shop for people to find out what's going on, without having to check their Facebook feeds.
qid279_text: No, beyond the "usual" ones. I wish there was a big site (Matong-like) with a river, so we could get some refresh in summer months, and perhaps even replace the burning effigy with a giant fountain, with water taken from the river (so we don't have to wheel it in)!
qid283_text: I would like to be less dependent on the expectations on US burns, including the presumed "need" to burn stuff. We are in the midst of climate change, and burning stuff is a questionable proposition at best. I wish our events were more sexy, and held in places and climates that encourage physical intimacy. There are examples of this in Europe, such as Nowhere (which is, in fact, an official regional Burn, despite them not burning anything).
qid284_text: Thank you so much for creating this survey! It's exactly what we needed <3

qid283_text: A supported space where inclusion is valued, but not at the expense of safety. An ongoing, viable, sustainable use of resources including financial, environmental and human. A community of individuals all working together to achieve common goals without a need to bend to individual egos. (Yeah, I know, I'm still idealistic!) Creation of spaces where people can be free to express themselves authentically. Continuously evolving methods of dealing with the less happy instances that will inevitably occur (like consent violations). More art, more variety of music, more random wonderful whirlwinds that we can get joyfully caught in.
qid284_text: Sadly, there's a lot of conversations I've had that the name "Seed" has become a cultural touchstone of trauma. Seed (and Matong) is the spiritual home of burning for me, but I accept that we need to move forwards into something new, we can't go back. This honestly has been such a process of grieving for me, and there's still a small part that hopes we can hold on to something of that place that previously existed. If cleverer minds than mine can come up with a way to achieve this, I'll support it to the hilt.

qid241_text: Workload balance, on site shifts for site mangers / rangers I feel are often too long. Perhaps more people would volunteer if shifts were shorter?   Communications / working as a team training for people in leadership roles,
qid243_text: There are often a few big personalities that take over or do not like to budge that makes working as a team challenging. Perhaps some self reflection and training on different communication style, how to work well as a team in a respectful way would be beneficial
qid244_text: Workload generally falls on a few key people, on site camp members can be flaky or not take initiative so constant coming to leads. Communications with organisers can be challenging, often last minute requests that should have been communicated sooner case issues for leads e.g. “now we need all camps to fill a site manager role” camps are already doing the heavy lifting in creating what brings people to the burn and finding suitable people to fill those roles is challenging, asking this a week before the event when shift schedules and planning is already finalised puts unfair pressure on theme camp leads.
qid245_text: Yes spice, Devon and other smaller camps at 3rd degree went really well and the previous year with a different camp at 3rd degree. Spice often do pop ups / take overs of other camps as well.

qid276_text: The many smaller events and offshoots from camps have created more options for people to burn. Smaller sites are generally easier than a large paddock with no infrastructure.

qid247_text: Who couldn’t use more money to make their art? As you start to make bigger pieces you need more space and the grants do not cover rent, and if you make art that does not get used elsewhere it is just a lost cost. If you do not have a big network it is hard to run a fundraiser so usually rent comes out of pocket. Having grants towards transport or shared paid for transport  is good as that is another big cost that is usually not considered. It was great that Seed also started allowing multi-year payments towards items like generators or equipment like lights that you might use again, especially if you could share with the artist beside you.

qid241_text: Workload balance for sure; understanding that people are gifting their time (especially in a pre-event role), and being respectful of boundaries that are set. Cajoling people into volunteering more than they already have, or biting off more than they can chew can be discouraging from me wanting to volunteer in a major way for that burn in future. Most of us have full time jobs, some have families, our downtime is limited as is.

qid282_text: Kangaroo Valley and Berry both have pretty lively 'hippie' scenes and could potentially be open to conversations about hosting burns. They're both go-to's for weekend trips for us because they're very queerdo friendly.
qid283_text: From an attendee perspective, Burning Seed in 2019 was the perfect sweet spot for me. A lively collection of theme camps, a beautiful collection of burnable art, and a community that seemed truly together. I would love to see Burns return to a place like this, of togetherness on a massive scale. Burners shouldn't need to travel to other states to find a Burn to feel truly at Home at, I want us to return to that place. To be a state that can proudly show a community capable of creating beautiful things, like Modifyre and Blazing Swan.
qid284_text: I think its important to consider the time of year when you consider ticket prices, I did try to clarify my answers but the bubbles were restricted to numerals only. I think the price of Metamorphosis would have gone down better if it weren't at the coldest time of year, and conversely I think people would have been more willing to attend at a suboptimal time of year if the ticket prices had been a little bit lower.  Operating at a loss for an org's first event is not unheard of, even if it is unpleasant. As I mentioned in my answers earlier, I think people were deterred by a perceived lack of compromise in the burn time of year.

qid284_text: Feels like the last big burn that got cancelled was too late in their organisation and didn't take into account that people won't camp in wagga in June. Kept telling us it was the same as Sept, not cold, and people posting in the FB groups we were wuss bags. People didn't want to go that far for that long when it could be that cold in June. Plain and simple. Yes, we understand the why they did the date as they did, for fire bans etc. We still could not go.  I also really appreciate the skill and knowledge we have in the collective community. Those who keep driving this community and events. I feel very fortunate we have people who continuously show up and do this. It takes a lot of their time.  I would get more involved in some degree if there was less bitchiness and less in fighting. Had a bad experience with one theme camp that wasn't pleasant. At the end of the day we are all in this for the same reason, and it should be fun. Not a punish. The EDM/Burner/Doof scene is a rare space of radical acceptance, temporary autonomy, and collective euphoria—a "suspension of the default world" where identity, capitalism, and social hierarchies dissolve in favor of pure expression.

qid283_text: "My vision for Burns in NSW is a fusion of radical hedonism and political awakening—where temporary utopias become training grounds for permanent resistance. Imagine doofs with anti-capitalist teach-ins, DJs soundtracking climate justice, and sunrise actions that extend beyond the dancefloor. It’s about transforming escapism into embodied solidarity, merging Burner principles with Naomi Klein’s ‘shock resistance’ to fight fascism and climate collapse."
qid284_text: What’s Missing:  - The Bridge to Political Action – The scene ignores its own power to resist the "shock doctrine" (fascism, climate collapse, late-stage capitalism).  - Lack of Sustained Solidarity – The party ends, but the system remains. Where’s the permanent movement?   -Escapism Without Strategy – A weekend of freedom is not enough when billionaires and far-right forces are weaponizing crises.

qid299_text: The experience we had in 2019 was amazing, and we all agree that we'd go again, but the kids say they'd go for 5 days, and that 10 was too long for them to really enjoy the experience. Overall, we understood that we needed to bring everything we needed, so in terms of what would make the experience better I think it really comes down to the organisation of the event. The 2019 event was, from what I observed a very good example of how things should be done. Safety was paramount, everyone looked out for their mates, no one left rubbish behind and the booze flowed freely and when it ran out no one complained. Another one like that please!
qid251_9_text: Sensitivity to lights and sounds, which increase in intensity when I am tired or stressed. My kids are all neurospicy but generally we are all able to manage our needs and environment well these days.
qid236_text: The experience we had in 2019 (which I think was the last time a full Seed was held?) was exceptional in terms of culture and community. The incentive to manage yourself and your crew successfully was in hosting a space where creativity was encouraged, communication was fostered and you felt heard and supported by multiple layers of crew, from your friends who camped with you, to the volunteers, to the staff, to the community liaisons, members and emergency services people who all had a vested interest in making the event as good as it possibly could be.
qid241_text: Distance will be the challenge to overcome when it comes to my participation beyond a punter role, since I live in Warrnbool Victoria. qid241_text: I think there were a lot of extraneous roles last burn (embers) that didn’t really seem necessary for the size of the burn. Thinking the two people in sanctuary all night all three nights without a single incident requiring their attention etc. think some of this could be better managed through someone being on call with a walkie talkie. I know some folks get a kick out of this stuff but I actually think there were more volunteer roles than were necessary and folks time wasn’t really valued.
qid243_text: Better comms in burn coordination. Lots of very noisy chat groups with poorly structured comms so you have to wade through loads of messages between individuals broadcasting to everyone. We’ve also put work into expectation setting so folks understand the commitments of joining our camp.
qid244_text: We put a lot of work into putting a filter on member recruitment, essentially creating a survey, vouching process and in some instances interviews to ensure the camp is safe (in terms of consent practice, respect etc). We also have had to create a mini not for profit entity to organise finances which has involved some extra admin but ultimately necessary. So yeah getting folks to do the boring bits like finances, AGMs etc has been a challenge at times but it’s been easy to get enthusiasm for builds, logistics, volunteering etc
qid245_text: We have mixed events eg traded Djs and venues. We also plan to provide infrastructure to other folks events more this year.
qid248_text: One big annual burn for the east coast, a smaller burns for regional gatherings near each major city, other burner parties and gatherings at least every month
qid276_text: There’s a solid core
qid307_text: The lack of a big burn means we’re not recruiting new burners and not connecting with our interstate burners. Means the community is getting older and smaller over time.
qid279_text: There’s plenty of awesome sites around St Albans / Wisemans Ferry for small regional burns. The 3rd degree site seems to work pretty well too.
qid282_text: I think we could do a better job of recruiting new burners by recruiting outside our bubble at larger parties and festivals. There are quite a few festivals that are ‘burner adjacent’ eg dragon dreaming, subsonic, confest, where we could potentially establish a presence and cross promote, but also make it clear the community provides a fun inclusive space (rather than an exclusive club)
qid283_text: A thriving, playful, inclusive and creative community that generates fleeting visions of a more connected, progressive and liberated way of life.
qid284_text: Thanks for preparing this survey. I think the crux is climate change is narrowing our window for burns in Australia and we might need to evolve. I don’t need a burn at every burner festival I attend. I also think the lack of a large burner event is killing our momentum as the events aren’t big enough to recruit new burners out of our own bubbles. The core organizers are all getting older and that’s not a good sign of a thriving community (look at the church!). Think we might need to think laterally about how to recruit younger burners and make sure they feel welcome when they  arrive.

qid284_text: 1. I take great issue with the volume of new wood that is used in constructing the effigy/ temple burns. I would love to see reused timber and wood from site used.  2.  Outside of the desert/salt flats of the original burning man site the idea of leave no trace is wholly  delusional and a false narrative.  Pretending that there can be 100s/1000s of people travelling to and stomping around a place for a week and that if they take their rubbish with them, it's as if they weren't there is just not ok. Acknowledge that we are/were there and leave a positive trace. Tree/ grass planting, erosion control, weed control, ect ask local mob what the country needs.  3. I'd love to see burner culture become more ecological responsible. I find the the volume of waste it produces utterly reprehensible.  Finnaly, every other aspect I absolutely fucking adore. I find it so so enriching  and I want burner culture to be apart of my life for the rest of my life.  Thank you 💙🦆💜

qid236_text: Complete liberation, expression, community, art, music, science, connection, being in nature, exploration of identity both personal and collective, education, a blissful alternate reality
qid241_text: Clear training and instructions, solid handover process, backup volunteers (often there are more than really needed on each shift but no-one to backfill if someone doesn’t show), workload balance, more flexibility in signing up, e.g. publish a spreadsheet where people can jump in and allocate themselves to shifts rather than emailing back and forth with one or two co-ordinators, which causes more work for them and means you often get allocated against a shift you can’t do, then have to try and trade, which is messy, and means there’s no guarantee you can do another shift by the time they email back because no slots work out, and you’re also trying to co-ordinate with people you’re travelling with to ensure you can make the start time etc. etc.
qid248_text: I think one nice thing (a silver lining) to come out of the unfortunate unpleasantness with the collapse of Seed is that many smaller burns have popped up in its place. This has been great for the diversity of the scene and the availability of closer, shorter burns for all meaning with other commitments people are more likely to be able to attend. I do think one big annual burn is important to connect all the interstate burners and theme camps. I would love to see the return of Seed. A nice range would be great. More regional single night events would be fun too, and potentially good fundraisers.  Re the below about having something to burn, I do think it’s very important but the question necessitates that it’s large scale, which I don’t think is important at all. That may help with fire organisation (restrictions, transport, etc.).
qid276_text: Lots more events recently  Initiatives like this survey to involve the community, give transparency, and foster a sense of identity
qid307_text: Call outs for opportunity for involvement  Working groups/steering committees on major or impactful decisions  The ability to vote on these things  Opportunities for feedback on issues or simple suggestions of how things could run better  Transparency over proceedings and decision making - better comms around this would do wonders to quell the rumour mill
qid279_text: I think a broader call out for properties would be a great idea  Camp Bunya (on Hipcamp/AirBnB) is relatively cheap and a great site for smaller events
qid281_text: A CoP or simile network would be useful here (once built)
qid282_text: Local re/upcycling organisations could be handy, links with communal spaces for events, city and regional maker spaces and similar organisations, places where offcut type supplies might be found (building supplies, Hard Rubbish etc.), having some people on side in councils would be handy
qid309_text: $100-150, but this depends heavily on variables like the venue, infrastructure, etc. - things could be done really bare bones if that was an experience people wanted, but cheaply
qid283_text: More is more! More diverse, more vibrant, more performance, more involvement, more teams of organisers so the same people aren’t always getting burnt out, more fun, more connection, more seasons.
qid284_text: Thank you for running this survey. I look forward to more!
